04257nam a22007095i 9789048541416DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182019ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485414167 a10.1515/97890485414162doi  a(DE-B1597)525253  a(OCoLC)1089011089  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0150802bisacsh04a700.9461 aStoenescu, Livia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Pictorial Art of El Greco :bTransmaterialities, Temporalities, and Media /cLivia Stoenescu. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (322 p.) :b10 color plates, 100 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVisual and Material Culture, 1300 –170000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Prototypal Images Reaffirmed in Early Modern Painting -- t2. Spanish Miraculous Images, Sacred Narratives, and Aesthetic Goals -- t3. El Greco’s The Purification of the Temple -- t4. Reinventing the Nude in an Age of Censorship -- t5. The Dialogue of Classical and Devotional Cultures in El Greco’s Laocoön of Toledo -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book investigates El Greco's pictorial art as foundational to the globalising trends manifested in the visual culture of early modernity. It also exposes the figurative, semantic, and allegorical senses he created to challenge an Italian Renaissance-centered discourse. Even though he was guided by the unprecedented flowering of devotional art in the post-Tridentine decades and by the expressive possibilities of earlier religious artifacts, especially those inherited from the apostolic past, the author demonstrates that El Greco forged his own independent trajectory. While his paintings have been studied in relation to the Italian and Spanish school traditions, his pictorial art in a global Mediterranean context continues to receive scant attention. Taking a global perspective as its focus, the book sheds new light on El Greco's highly original contribution to early Mediterranean and multi-institutional configurations of the Christian faith in Byzantium, Venice, Rome, Toledo, and Madrid.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aHistory. 4aLate Middle Ages & Renaissance. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aEl Greco, early modern painting, Mediterranean studies, Renaissance art, transmaterialities of religious imagery.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066731808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066152140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048541416zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048541416423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048541416/original  a978-3-11-066152-1  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-066731-8  AUP eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK